# Rebuild and Restart After Code Changes

After editing any source file (e.g. `*.c`, `*.h`, Makefile) in this project:

1. **Run a full rebuild.** If the build succeeds, **stop any running instance and start the new binary**:
   ```bash
   cd /home/damon/arrival_board && make clean && make -j USE_SDL_IMAGE=1 && make stop && ./arrival_board &
   ```
   - `make clean && make -j USE_SDL_IMAGE=1`: full rebuild.
   - If build fails, the command stops and the old process is left running.
   - If build succeeds: `make stop` kills any running arrival_board/run script, then `./arrival_board &` runs the new binary in the background.

2. Reboot does **not** recompile; only `make` does. The running process must be stopped (e.g. `make stop`) before the new binary can use the display.

If you make changes but don't rebuild and restart, the running `arrival_board` binary is unchanged and the user will not see your fixes.
